son overcrowding comprises nine chapters by leading academic experts, who expose these proposals to critical scrutiny. They take the Carter Report to task for construing the problems too narrowly, in terms of efficiency and economy, and for failing to understand the wider issues of justice that need addressing. They argue that the crisis of prison overcrowding is first and foremost a political problem - arising from penal populism - for which political solutions need to be found. This accessible report will be of interest to policy makers, probation practitioners, academics and other commentators on criminal policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aPrison administrationzGreat BritainvCongresses. 0aPrisonsxCongressesxGovernment policyzGreat BritainxGrossbritannien. 0aPrisonsxGovernment policyzGreat BritainvCongresses. 0aPrisonsxOvercrowdingzGreat BritainvCongresses. 0aPrisonszGreat BritainxCongressesxOvercrowding. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Rob, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHedderman, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHough, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHough, Mike, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJacobson, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacey, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiebling, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Rod, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSachdev, Sanjiv, econtributor.4ctb